@xingyaoww @neubig - I think we need to re-think the whole `Message` pydantic-class approach introduced with the initial images support.
The implementation seems to work with Anthropic models, but then also got extended with the caching option/extra headers (which are also only for select models).
The class has the `type` attribute on the message level, which causes bad request errors for e.g. Gemini (on different providers) and Groq API.

To circumvent that, now messages have to be "converted" back to a flat text content to make them compatible again.
We need to look if there is a "general" format that litellm expects images in OR if it just passes them on 1:1.
In the latter case, we may have to introduce provider/API(?)-specific message construction to fill the right attributes.

As for right now, I'd recommend we should get this PR in (several users waiting) and in a follow-up PR take care of further issues/details for this.

Looking at the **Groq API** docs as an example, they do support passing images, but in a different format:
![grafik](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9f540448-8639-43b8-8fdd-a592fcb2140a)

-----

As per **Anthropic**'s [cookbook](https://github.com/anthropics/anthropic-cookbook/blob/main/multimodal/best_practices_for_vision.ipynb), an example messages list prep in Python for vision can look like this:
```
message_list = [
    {
        "role": 'user',
        "content": [
            {"type": "image", "source": {"type": "base64", "media_type": "image/jpeg", "data": get_base64_encoded_image("../images/best_practices/nine_dogs.jpg")}},
            {"type": "text", "text": "How many dogs are in this picture?"}
        ]
    }
]
```

-----

For **ChatGPT** vision models I found this example:
```messages=[
            {
                "role": "user",
                "content": [
                    {"type": "text", "text": "How many cats are in the image?"},
                    {"type": "image_url", "image_url": {"url": img_str}}
                ],
            }
        ],
```

